bonic Acid” -- t9 Removing the “Brand of Shame,” Rehabilitating Armenian Skin -- tREMNANT 8: “Tattooed Like an Arab,” Serpouhi Tavoukdjian -- t10 Counternarratives of Tribal Tattoos and Survivor Agency -- tPART III Bones -- tREMNANT 9: A Lamentation: “In the Deserts of Dayr al-Zur” (Der Zor çöllerinde) -- t11 If These Bones Could Speak: Early Armenian Pilgrimages to Dayr al-Zur -- t12 Feeling Their Way through the Desert: Affective Itineraries of “Non-Sites of Memory” -- t13 Bone Memory: Community, Ritual, and Memory Work in the Syrian Desert -- tEPILOGUE Bone on Bone -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA groundbreaking and profoundly moving exploration of the Armenian genocide, told through the traces left in the memories and on the bodies of its women survivors. Foremost among the images of the Armenian Genocide is the specter of tattooed Islamized Armenian women. Blue tribal tattoos that covered face and body signified assimilation into Muslim Bedouin and Kurdish households. Among Armenians, the tattooed survivor was seen as a living ethnomartyr or, alternatively, a national stain, and the bodies of women and children figured centrally within the Armenian communal memory and humanitarian imaginary. In Remnants, these tattooed and scar-bearing bodies reveal a larger history, as the lived trauma of genocide is understood through bodies, skin, and—in what remains of those lives a century afterward—bones. With this book, Elyse Semerdjian offers a feminist reading of the Armenian Genocide. She explores how the Ottoman Armenian communal body was dis-membered, disfigured, and later re-membered by the survivor community. Gathering individual memories and archival fragments, she writes a deeply personal history, and issues a call to break open the archival record in order to embrace affect and memory. Traces of women and children rescued during and after the war are reconstructed to center the quietest voices in the historical record. This daring work embraces physical and archival remnants, the imprinted negatives of once living bodies, as a space of radical possibility within Armenian prosthetic memory and a necessary way to recognize the absence that remains.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArmenian Genocide survivorsxHistory. 0aArmenian Genocide, 1915-1923xPsychological aspects. 0aCollective memoryzArmenia. 0aHuman bodyxSymbolic aspects. 0aWomen genocide survivorsxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  aBones.  aGender.  aGenocide.  aHumanitarianism.  aMemory.  aPilgrimage.  aSexual Atrocity.  aTattoos.1 aHerian, Ruben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363613240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503636132423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503636132/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131913-1  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2023  aZDB-23-DGGb2023